Gil, 

It&#39;s not really an error; it&#39;s just that the code can&#39;t figure out how to represent this 
reaction on a reaction path diagram, so it will ignore it when constructing the 
diagram. The problem is that to trace the flow of an element through the species it is 
necessary to know which atom of which reactant ends up in which product. Consider 
the reaction

HCO + OH = CO + H2O

Cantera doesn&#39;t know if the oxygen in H2O came from OH or from HCO, and therefore 
doesn&#39;t know if an arrow should connect the HCO node to H2O, or the OH node to 
H2O.  There used to be a way you could specify this directly in Chemkin-format files 
by adding a comment like

!% H-CO + OH = CO + H-OH

to specify that the HCO H atom transfers, instead of breaking 2 bonds:

!% HO-C + O-H = HO-H + C-O

But this capability was lost in version 1.5, with the introduction of the new &#39;cti&#39; format 
(which I would recommend over writing raw CTML markup).  I&#39;ll add it to the cti format 
&#39;soon.&#39;

Without such a specification, Cantera relies on some rules to make a default choice. 
The rules, however, only work for reactions of the form 

AB + C = AC + B

where A, B, and C are arbitrary groups. Cantera doesn&#39;t have a rule to handle 
reactions that have 3 products, as yours does. If you want to keep this reaction, you 
can get Cantera 1.4; alternatively, you can decompose the reaction into elementary 
ones of the above form, or else simply let Cantera exclude it from the diagram. 

Hope this helps.
Dave




